WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.280
So thank you, everyone. My name is Edgar Ruiz.

00:00:03.280 --> 00:00:05.520
I work with the Sparkly R package.

00:00:05.520 --> 00:00:09.600
So I've been doing large-scale implementations

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:12.320
that have to do with implementing R,

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:18.680
as well as being able to work with SQL and, in this case, Spark.

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:20.879
And what I'm going to talk about today is

00:00:20.879 --> 00:00:24.040
its implementation with a new kind of Spark,

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:26.120
which is Spark Connect.

00:00:26.120 --> 00:00:28.680
So I'll start right there.

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:31.240
With Spark Connect, it's something that started

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:35.200
in a very, very recent version of Spark, 3.4.

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:39.040
In fact, it's so recent that 3.5 literally came out yesterday.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:41.680
So we're talking about that close.

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:44.959
And with Spark Connect, it's not so much a new way of implementing,

00:00:44.959 --> 00:00:48.279
like you have standalone or Kubernetes or Yarn.

00:00:48.279 --> 00:00:51.200
This is more about how you connect to Spark, right?

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:55.720
So if we're talking about a remote way of connecting to Spark

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:58.880
as it used to be before, that was through something called Livy.

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:00.880
And in order for us to use Livy,

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:02.840
we needed to have a full-on implementation

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:05.879
of a Yarn-based cluster, such as Hadoop cluster,

00:01:05.879 --> 00:01:09.080
to be able to take advantage of that service,

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:12.320
which is not ideal in the new world that we live in,

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:15.599
where most of our data is now in S3 buckets, right?

00:01:15.599 --> 00:01:18.400
All we need right now is not so much a place to land our data,

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:21.959
like Hadoop does, but more about how to process it, right?

00:01:21.959 --> 00:01:25.279
A way to process it easily, which is through Spark, right?

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:27.839
So with Spark Connect, it's basically doing that for us,

00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:30.440
where we can actually have a Spark cluster

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:34.199
that we can actually interact with remotely, right?

00:01:34.199 --> 00:01:39.519
In our laptops, we can easily go back and forth and interact with it.

00:01:39.519 --> 00:01:43.760
Databricks Connect, version 13 plus,

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:47.599
have Spark Connect, it's based on that.

00:01:47.599 --> 00:01:50.239
So you'll be able to take advantage of it

00:01:50.239 --> 00:01:53.800
if you're currently using it or think about using it.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:55.639
So how does it work?

00:01:55.639 --> 00:01:57.839
Well, underneath it, instead of doing like

00:01:57.839 --> 00:02:01.080
straight-up REST APIs like it used to be with Libby,

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:04.599
Spark Connect is using gRPC,

00:02:04.599 --> 00:02:08.399
which actually works as that layer of communication.

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:11.160
And at this point, I can confidently say that

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:17.639
the best way to interact with that gRPC is through PySpark.

00:02:17.639 --> 00:02:23.399
So PySpark will use other Python libraries that implement gRPC,

00:02:23.399 --> 00:02:26.160
and then talk to Spark.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:28.160
For the machine learning stuff,

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:30.199
which again just came out yesterday,

00:02:30.199 --> 00:02:32.800
it's going to be done through Torch.

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:35.240
And right now, there's like I believe

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:38.800
one machine learning model implemented in a new version.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:40.839
So what about R, right?

00:02:40.839 --> 00:02:42.240
What about Sparkly R?

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:45.919
Well, because of the implementation that's going on with PySpark,

00:02:45.919 --> 00:02:49.520
we made the call to go ahead and integrate through that library.

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:50.679
And in order to do that,

00:02:50.679 --> 00:02:52.559
we're using the reticulate package.

00:02:52.559 --> 00:02:54.039
So if you're not familiar with it,

00:02:54.039 --> 00:02:56.759
this is the package that in R allows us to

00:02:56.759 --> 00:02:59.399
integrate with Python directly from our R session,

00:02:59.399 --> 00:03:01.960
so we can have two-way communication with it.

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:04.399
So as you can see in this little diagram,

00:03:04.399 --> 00:03:08.720
you can go from reticulate to PySpark into the Spark cluster.

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:11.119
So the question is, okay, if I can do this from reticulate,

00:03:11.119 --> 00:03:12.800
why do I need Sparkly R for?

00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:15.440
Well, if you are a user today,

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:18.559
you know that Sparkly R does other things, right?

00:03:18.559 --> 00:03:21.639
It gives you that interface for dplyr,

00:03:21.639 --> 00:03:24.119
so you can use dplyr commands to interact with Spark.

00:03:24.119 --> 00:03:25.800
You can also use DBI,

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:27.880
and also the connection panes,

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:31.000
as well as other very easy-to-use functions

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.320
that as data scientists,

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:35.320
we use to run models and things like that.

00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:38.880
The other great thing that I'm very excited about is like,

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:40.080
once you start using it,

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:42.839
you don't have to have Java installed in your computer anymore.

00:03:42.839 --> 00:03:47.960
This has been the subject of a lot of heartache for a lot of us,

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:49.199
to have Java working.

00:03:49.199 --> 00:03:50.919
Well, because it's all remote,

00:03:50.919 --> 00:03:53.279
and because it's using this GRCP,

00:03:53.279 --> 00:03:55.520
you don't have to worry about that anymore.

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:57.360
To get started, it's very easy.

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:00.559
You would use the latest version of Sparkly R,

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:04.520
as well as the way that we've chosen to implement it at this time,

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:07.639
which is through an extension package called PySparkly R,

00:04:07.639 --> 00:04:12.039
that you will install from GitHub.

00:04:12.039 --> 00:04:15.080
Hopefully, we'll have this in Cranberry soon.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:19.959
So all you have to do is upgrade your Sparkly R, install it.

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:23.519
Then to get the Python components that you'll need,

00:04:23.519 --> 00:04:27.839
PySparkly R gives you a convenience function that will install

00:04:27.839 --> 00:04:30.079
all the Python libraries that you will need

00:04:30.079 --> 00:04:32.720
to use in order to get it working.

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:37.200
So if you're a Python user already and you're saying,

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:41.640
I don't need the convenience function, I can do it myself.

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:43.760
These are the packages that you'll need.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:48.559
There is a requirement for you to have Python 3.9 or above.

00:04:48.559 --> 00:04:52.200
If you are an R user and the other way around,

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:54.600
you don't really want to mess too much with Python,

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:55.799
that's totally fine too.

00:04:55.799 --> 00:04:57.959
I feel exactly the same way.

00:04:57.959 --> 00:04:59.920
So I've gone through the pain of doing all this

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:03.160
and putting all the stuff that you need in that function.

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:05.839
If you don't have 3.9 available in your laptop,

00:05:05.839 --> 00:05:07.600
it'll warn you and it'll give you some tips

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:10.440
on how to do your upgrade if you need to.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:14.600
You can also run Spark Connect locally.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:18.279
So this is something that we're used to

00:05:18.279 --> 00:05:20.799
as we start learning Spark.

00:05:20.799 --> 00:05:25.440
We run Spark locally and what it does is start Spark

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:27.559
and then whenever you do a connection

00:05:27.559 --> 00:05:30.519
and actually it stops the service when you disconnect.

00:05:30.519 --> 00:05:32.720
For Spark Connect, it's going to be a little bit different.

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:34.760
You're going to have to start the service separate

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:37.279
and then stop it separate from your connection.

00:05:37.279 --> 00:05:39.519
At this point, we can actually make

00:05:39.519 --> 00:05:41.920
this function a little bit better, a bit more convenient.

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:44.320
We have it available now and we're definitely

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.959
going to be improving it to make it easier to use.

00:05:46.959 --> 00:05:49.040
Actually, not so much easier to use but have

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:51.799
more customizations and things that you can do with it.

00:05:51.799 --> 00:05:54.640
So now we come to Databricks Connect.

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:59.119
So how does that connect to Databricks Connect?

00:05:59.119 --> 00:06:03.279
So if you're a customer of working with Databricks before,

00:06:03.279 --> 00:06:06.480
you heard Databricks Connect before, that term.

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:10.920
But now you also hear the term Databricks Connect v2.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:13.399
So that version two is what we're talking about now

00:06:13.399 --> 00:06:17.239
that started with Spark 3.4 through the Spark Connect,

00:06:17.239 --> 00:06:20.679
that is going to be available in DBR 13 and above.

00:06:20.679 --> 00:06:24.359
Databricks Connect, same thing as Spark Connect,

00:06:24.359 --> 00:06:28.399
now you can use your laptop to be able to interact with Spark.

00:06:28.399 --> 00:06:31.320
So you don't have to be inside the environment,

00:06:31.320 --> 00:06:33.640
inside Databricks and open our studio there and all that.

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:35.679
You can actually do that on your laptop.

00:06:35.679 --> 00:06:37.239
In order to do that today,

00:06:37.239 --> 00:06:39.040
you're able to connect.

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:40.480
You'll need four things,

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:42.119
which is the master and that will be

00:06:42.119 --> 00:06:45.799
the URL for the Databricks of your organization,

00:06:45.799 --> 00:06:48.079
the cluster ID that you want to work with,

00:06:48.079 --> 00:06:51.760
also your personal token that you can also get from Databricks,

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:55.279
and the method which will be Databricks underscore

00:06:55.279 --> 00:07:00.200
connect as opposed to Databricks dash connect or Databricks.

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:01.720
So we try to make it as confusing as

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:03.720
possible for you and I apologize for that.

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:08.359
So but we have a lot of warnings that hopefully will get you there.

00:07:08.359 --> 00:07:11.760
All right. So the other thing that we want to do is

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:14.760
these two environment variables Databricks host and

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:17.279
Databricks token are becoming very standardized right

00:07:17.279 --> 00:07:18.920
now across different applications as

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:21.279
you start working with Databricks Connect V2.

00:07:21.279 --> 00:07:23.760
So Sparkly R picks them up.

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:26.440
So that way whenever you connect to your cluster,

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:27.880
you don't need to set them all up.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:29.279
You basically just provide

00:07:29.279 --> 00:07:33.119
your cluster ID and your Databricks Connect method.

00:07:33.119 --> 00:07:35.000
Of course, please, please,

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.040
please use your Databricks token in an environment variable.

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:41.239
Do not put your credentials in an open text for your code.

00:07:41.239 --> 00:07:44.200
Definitely best practices.

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:50.359
Because we're able to do that integration directly to PySpark,

00:07:50.359 --> 00:07:53.399
we're getting a lot of nice goodies to integrate better.

00:07:53.399 --> 00:07:55.640
So this is the Unity catalog where you can see

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:59.640
your tables inside the Databricks web UI.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:01.480
Well, now that's inside our studio.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:03.959
This is the first time in Sparkly R history

00:08:03.959 --> 00:08:06.040
that we're offering more than one layer.

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:08.799
Used to be that we would stop from table into a schema.

00:08:08.839 --> 00:08:10.760
Now we go the three layers all the way

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:12.880
to matching to what Databricks does.

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:16.760
So we can go from table to schema to catalog,

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:20.200
and that will make it where you can be here and have

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:25.119
the exact same navigational structure that you see inside UC.

00:08:25.119 --> 00:08:27.399
So that way it's a lot easier for you to be able

00:08:27.399 --> 00:08:30.000
to find the tables that you want to interact with.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:34.200
Of course, you can also preview the tables if you need to.

00:08:34.200 --> 00:08:36.039
By just clicking on it,

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:37.880
you'll see the first 1,000 rows.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:44.119
So that way that give you that visual first look of the data.

00:08:44.119 --> 00:08:48.559
Also accessing the catalog data is very easy now.

00:08:48.559 --> 00:08:52.320
DB Player has a new function called InCatalog.

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:54.559
So you may be aware of InSchema.

00:08:54.559 --> 00:08:56.280
This InCatalog gives you

00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:58.719
from a supposed schema with those two levels.

00:08:58.719 --> 00:09:00.599
InCatalog will do the three levels.

00:09:00.599 --> 00:09:01.799
So as you see,

00:09:01.799 --> 00:09:05.479
you have the three samples to NYC taxi to trips.

00:09:05.479 --> 00:09:07.599
You basically put that in the same order,

00:09:07.599 --> 00:09:09.080
inside the function call,

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:10.640
and you're good to go.

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:13.359
That creates the pointer to the table.

00:09:13.359 --> 00:09:16.400
Then now, whenever you just call the variable,

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:18.359
it's just going to bring you the top 10 rows.

00:09:18.359 --> 00:09:22.080
Because DB Player and Spark VR does

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:25.760
have those guardrails that prevent you from, or me.

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:27.559
I don't say you as in general,

00:09:27.559 --> 00:09:29.039
but me from be able to,

00:09:29.039 --> 00:09:32.799
when I do this, download the entire billion records.

00:09:32.799 --> 00:09:35.520
You can use those goodies again from

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:36.960
the stuff that we wrap around

00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:39.719
all this other communication with Spark.

00:09:39.719 --> 00:09:42.640
Once you have your table,

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:47.119
excuse me, your pointer, you can use DB Player as we do today.

00:09:47.119 --> 00:09:49.679
The same commands, you're able to

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:52.280
push all that computation to the cluster.

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:54.320
So instead of you having to download

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:55.679
the billions of records and then

00:09:55.679 --> 00:09:57.520
do the summarization in your laptop,

00:09:57.520 --> 00:10:00.200
you can just write your DB Player as you would.

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:03.520
You treat trips just as if it was a table that you have locally.

00:10:03.520 --> 00:10:08.440
What it does in the background is that it will

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:12.599
translate your DB Player commands into SQL.

00:10:12.599 --> 00:10:14.000
So all the computation,

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:15.760
all the aggregation is happening remotely,

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:17.359
and you're just getting back the results,

00:10:17.359 --> 00:10:19.760
which is the exact ideal way that you want to deal with

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:24.000
these kinds of database and big data backends.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.200
If you want to see the query that you're getting,

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:30.640
you can use show query and that will provide you that query.

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:33.280
Also coming soon, I'm very excited to talk

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:35.520
about this first time we're

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:39.479
actually showing it as far as the work that we're doing.

00:10:39.479 --> 00:10:44.799
Inside the Databricks WebUI again,

00:10:44.799 --> 00:10:47.440
you have where you can manage the clusters,

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:51.159
where you can start and stop a cluster and be able

00:10:51.159 --> 00:10:53.119
to basically get the information

00:10:53.119 --> 00:10:55.000
that you need in order to connect to it.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:59.359
Well, in a coming soon version of POSIT Workbench,

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:02.159
we'll be able to have that same ability

00:11:02.159 --> 00:11:04.760
inside a new pane, a Databricks pane.

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:08.799
That pane will match to what you see today in

00:11:08.799 --> 00:11:13.400
the WebUI where you can start and stop a cluster,

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:15.679
and you can also expand the details of

00:11:15.679 --> 00:11:18.039
a specific cluster and see

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:22.559
the same information that you would see in the WebUI.

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:24.179
So that way, again,

00:11:24.179 --> 00:11:26.640
you start in our studio and you end in our studio.

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:28.719
So we started with the catalog and now

00:11:28.719 --> 00:11:30.919
we're being able to

00:11:30.919 --> 00:11:34.119
administer the clusters by starting and stopping,

00:11:34.119 --> 00:11:36.400
and this is my favorite feature

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:40.280
because now the first time that you connect to a cluster.

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:42.440
Again, remember the only thing that

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:44.280
you will need will be the cluster ID.

00:11:44.280 --> 00:11:49.159
Well, the very genius folks that working on this solution,

00:11:49.159 --> 00:11:50.359
which is not me, by the way,

00:11:50.359 --> 00:11:51.919
this is the IDE folks,

00:11:51.919 --> 00:11:56.619
have put a copy button right there for you to get your cluster ID,

00:11:56.619 --> 00:12:01.059
which then you just paste it in your code and you're good to go.

00:12:01.059 --> 00:12:05.460
No problem, you start and end in our studio.

00:12:05.460 --> 00:12:08.299
Once you connect for the first time,

00:12:08.299 --> 00:12:10.219
then the connections pane takes

00:12:10.219 --> 00:12:12.380
over from what you've been using before.

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:15.500
You'll be able to have that connection.

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:18.619
So you end your work and you come back tomorrow,

00:12:18.619 --> 00:12:20.700
you'll have it right there, you click on it,

00:12:20.700 --> 00:12:23.219
it shows you the code that you used to connect,

00:12:23.219 --> 00:12:24.619
and then once you say,

00:12:24.619 --> 00:12:27.539
yes, I want to connect, you go right back to the Unity catalog.

00:12:27.539 --> 00:12:30.539
So I mean, this is really exciting for me

00:12:30.539 --> 00:12:34.659
because I'm sure a lot of folks who are working today with

00:12:34.659 --> 00:12:37.039
this environment will see

00:12:37.039 --> 00:12:38.859
a lot improvements when it comes to what we

00:12:38.859 --> 00:12:41.719
call quality of life as far as interacting with it.

00:12:41.719 --> 00:12:45.340
Some additional information, there's

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:48.419
some limitations right now with Spark 3.4 and 3.5,

00:12:48.419 --> 00:12:50.739
when it comes to Spark Connect.

00:12:51.739 --> 00:12:55.099
So what we support, as I mentioned before,

00:12:55.099 --> 00:12:57.659
we have the plier and DBI APIs,

00:12:57.659 --> 00:12:59.619
the vote command will work,

00:12:59.619 --> 00:13:01.659
the connections pane like I showed.

00:13:01.659 --> 00:13:07.200
Also, the personal authorization token will work.

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:08.840
We're actually also working.

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:11.380
Another thing I'm glad to announce on

00:13:11.380 --> 00:13:15.059
OAuth that will work directly from Workbench,

00:13:15.059 --> 00:13:19.179
and also most of the read and write commands work today.

00:13:19.179 --> 00:13:20.500
What's not supported, of course,

00:13:20.500 --> 00:13:25.419
especially in 3.4, which is what's right now GA available,

00:13:25.419 --> 00:13:30.059
is ML functions, SDF functions, and TidyR.

00:13:30.059 --> 00:13:32.260
Although, this is not right

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:34.380
because PivotLonger is available now,

00:13:34.380 --> 00:13:36.179
although not all arguments.

00:13:36.179 --> 00:13:37.500
So if you want to try

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:42.700
an existing PivotLonger code that you have in Spark Connect,

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:44.820
it will not ignore the arguments,

00:13:44.820 --> 00:13:46.260
it will just tell you that it's not supported.

00:13:46.260 --> 00:13:48.659
So it's safe for you to try out.

00:13:48.659 --> 00:13:51.859
Also, you can access entire API.

00:13:51.859 --> 00:13:55.419
So Spark VR will not have everything all the time,

00:13:55.419 --> 00:13:56.619
but you should be able to access

00:13:56.619 --> 00:13:58.659
everything as opposed to how it was before,

00:13:58.659 --> 00:14:00.780
that you had to wait on me to

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:02.700
go in and make the argument change

00:14:02.700 --> 00:14:04.619
because from one version to the next,

00:14:04.619 --> 00:14:07.179
add a new argument, now you have to wait for me to add it.

00:14:07.179 --> 00:14:08.780
You don't have to do that.

00:14:08.780 --> 00:14:10.619
You can actually, because of how

00:14:10.619 --> 00:14:13.159
Reticulate works and how it does the integration,

00:14:13.159 --> 00:14:15.780
you can access those Python objects directly.

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:18.299
So in here, I'm using

00:14:18.299 --> 00:14:24.140
the CreateDataFrame function from Python to add the empty cars.

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:26.059
Then when I pull it up,

00:14:26.059 --> 00:14:28.179
it's not printing the table like it does before.

00:14:28.179 --> 00:14:30.580
I can show you before, it's actually showing you

00:14:30.580 --> 00:14:34.940
that Python object that's been loaded into the Spark context.

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:38.739
Then I can access functions that are part of that DataFrame,

00:14:38.739 --> 00:14:41.059
in this case, correlations, for example.

00:14:41.059 --> 00:14:45.059
Obviously, this is not the way that you will be doing it day-to-day,

00:14:45.059 --> 00:14:48.460
but you can see that there's no limitations.

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:51.179
Another way that we can see that there's no limitations is

00:14:51.179 --> 00:14:52.900
like when you extend it with Reticulate,

00:14:52.900 --> 00:14:56.820
you can literally call the same Python libraries

00:14:56.820 --> 00:15:01.020
inside your RStudio sessions.

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:04.020
So in this case, for something so recent,

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:06.219
like literally yesterday started,

00:15:06.219 --> 00:15:12.900
you can go and get the MLConnect classification library,

00:15:12.900 --> 00:15:16.820
that then you can start accessing its functionality.

00:15:16.820 --> 00:15:20.859
Here, I'm using the same table empty cars,

00:15:20.859 --> 00:15:23.820
and I set up or I

00:15:23.820 --> 00:15:25.700
prepare it for me to be able to run

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:30.700
the machine learning algorithm.

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:33.859
Then I run it here and I fit it,

00:15:33.859 --> 00:15:36.739
I get my logistic regression,

00:15:36.739 --> 00:15:39.140
and then I can use it to do the transform,

00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:40.580
which is basically the predict,

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:43.900
and I extract the data to pandas through the pandas function,

00:15:43.900 --> 00:15:48.340
which gives me everything like the predictions here.

00:15:48.340 --> 00:15:53.099
You can see the predictions directly as

00:15:53.099 --> 00:15:57.059
new columns inside my DataFrame,

00:15:57.059 --> 00:15:59.299
which by the way, it's already inside R.

00:15:59.299 --> 00:16:02.659
So I run all the models out there and I can get the results back.

00:16:02.659 --> 00:16:05.179
This is just an example that obviously,

00:16:05.179 --> 00:16:11.059
we want for you to use the ML logistic regression function.

00:16:11.059 --> 00:16:13.900
But again, once those features are available,

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:15.460
we're not there yet, you can access them.

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:17.140
We're not locking you out here.

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:20.059
So in closing, SparkConnect will enable

00:16:20.059 --> 00:16:23.219
us to be able to communicate with Spark remotely.

00:16:23.219 --> 00:16:27.940
Databricks Connect, it has that enable on DBR 13 and above.

00:16:27.940 --> 00:16:30.979
We're using PySpark to reticulate,

00:16:30.979 --> 00:16:34.500
to integrate that in Sparkly R. Again,

00:16:34.500 --> 00:16:37.460
we're not limiting you, you can extend that with reticulate.

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:39.780
Here are some links that I'm going to put

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:43.179
because I want to thank you first of all for your attention,

00:16:43.179 --> 00:16:46.340
and here's the QR if you want to get to this presentation,

00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:50.380
which will have all the links that you need. Thank you so much.

